"# Chapter 6 — The Verb Pipeline

## What we're building toward

When you orchestrate several wired verbs so each stage feeds the next—output curls into input, close-data-close-paren—you're writing a *pipeline*. Each verb does one honest thing; together they compose a route that could not exist alone. This chapter drills that skill: chaining verbs, checking failure at every seam, and advancing a computation stage by stage until a complete answer surfaces.

The satisfaction here is *architectural*. A two-verb chain feels clever the first time you write one. A five-stage pipeline with failure handling at every joint feels like mastery—because it is. You're not calling functions; you're *routing data through the wired surface*, and the route itself becomes the program.

We'll start with short chains—fetch-then-parse, lookup-then-filter—and ramp up to longer orchestrations that cross namespaces, transform shape, and escalate cleanly when a stage can't proceed. By the end, you'll write programs where the verbs themselves are the structure, and the data flows like water.

When the runtime can do this, she can *compose capabilities*. A single verb is a tool; a pipeline is a workshop.

---

## Two-verb chains: the simplest pipeline

The simplest pipeline is two verbs where the second consumes the first's output. No intermediate binding; the result of verb A becomes the argument to verb B. If either fails, the whole route escalates honestly—we check, we don't assume.

### Fetch a page, then count its words

```scheme
;; Fetch a public webpage and count how many words it contains.
;; If fetch fails, surface the failure; if word-count fails, surface that.

(let ((page (web/fetch \"https://example.com\")))
  (if (or (eq? page 'nan)
          (and (pair? page) (eq? (car page) 'escalate)))
      page  ; surface the failure
      (let ((count (text/word-count page)))
        (if (eq? count 'nan)
            '(escalate \"word-count-failed\" \"could not parse text\")
            count))))
```

Two stages: `web/fetch` yields text, `text/word-count` yields a number. We check after each. If either returns `'nan` or an escalation, we surface it. If both succeed, the count emerges.

This is FORWARD: each stage advances the computation. This is ESCAPE: we route failure cleanly, never faking a result.

---

### Geocode an address, then find its timezone offset

```scheme
;; Turn a street address into coordinates, then infer the timezone offset.
;; If geocoding fails, escalate; if time/now fails, escalate; else return offset.

(let ((coords (geo/geocode-address \"1600 Amphitheatre Parkway, Mountain View, CA\")))
  (if (or (eq? coords 'nan)
          (and (pair? coords) (eq? (car coords) 'escalate)))
      coords
      ;; coords is an alist with 'lat and 'lng; we don't have a timezone-from-coords verb,
      ;; so we demonstrate the *pattern* by using time/now at the current location.
      ;; In a real pipeline, you'd call a timezone verb here if one existed.
      (let ((now (time/now)))
        (if (eq? now 'nan)
            '(escalate \"time-failed\" \"could not read current time\")
            ;; Construct a result showing we'd route coords -> timezone.
            (list (cons 'address \"1600 Amphitheatre Parkway, Mountain View, CA\")
                  (cons 'coords coords)
                  (cons 'timestamp now))))))
```

Two verbs, two checks. The pattern is identical: verb, test, advance or escalate. This is the rhythm of every pipeline.

