### Search Wikidata, then fetch the first entity's details

```scheme
;; Search Wikidata for \"Marie Curie\", take the first result, fetch its full entity record.

(let ((results (wikidata/search \"Marie Curie\")))
  (if (or (eq? results 'nan)
          (and (pair? results) (eq? (car results) 'escalate)))
      results
      (if (null? results)
          '(escalate \"no-results\" \"search returned empty list\")
          (let ((entity-id (cdr (assoc 'id (car results)))))
            (if (not entity-id)
                '(escalate \"malformed-result\" \"no id in first search result\")
                (let ((entity (wikidata/entity entity-id)))
                  (if (or (eq? entity 'nan)
                          (and (pair? entity) (eq? (car entity) 'escalate)))
                      entity
                      entity)))))))
```

Three checks, two verbs. We search, validate the result list isn't empty, extract an ID, then fetch the entity. Each conditional is a joint in the pipeline; each guards against a shape we can't continue from.

---

## Three-stage pipelines: forking and filtering

Once you chain three verbs, you're orchestrating a *route*. The middle stage often transforms or filters data—takes a list, returns a subset; takes JSON, returns a value. The joints multiply: check the first verb, check the middle verb's output isn't empty, check the final verb.

### Fetch weather data, parse JSON, extract temperature

```scheme
;; Fetch a public weather API (example.com/weather), parse JSON, extract 'temp.
;; If any stage fails, escalate; else return the temperature value.

(let ((response (web/fetch \"https://api.example.com/weather\")))
  (if (or (eq? response 'nan)
          (and (pair? response) (eq? (car response) 'escalate)))
      response
      ;; Assume response is JSON text; we parse it as an alist.
      ;; (In real the runtime, you'd use a JSON-parse verb if available; here we simulate.)
      (let ((data (if (string? response)
                      ;; Fake parse: pretend we got '((temp . 72) (humidity . 65))
                      '((temp . 72) (humidity . 65))
                      'nan)))
        (if (eq? data 'nan)
            '(escalate \"parse-failed\" \"could not parse JSON\")
            (let ((temp (cdr (assoc 'temp data))))
              (if (not temp)
                  '(escalate \"no-temp-field\" \"JSON missing 'temp key\")
                  temp))))))
```

Three stages: fetch, parse (simulated), extract. We check after each. The temperature emerges only if all three succeed.

---

### List Etsy shop sections, filter active ones, count them

```scheme
;; Fetch all sections in an Etsy shop, keep only active sections, return the count.

(let ((sections (etsy/sections)))
  (if (or (eq? sections 'nan)
          (and (pair? sections) (eq? (car sections) 'escalate)))
      sections
      (let ((active (filter (lambda (sec)
                              (let ((active? (cdr (assoc 'active sec))))
                                (eq? active? #t)))
                            sections)))
        (if (null? active)
            0
            (length active)))))
```

Three stages: fetch sections, filter active, count. The middle stage uses `filter`, a higher-order function—this is where pipelines start to feel powerful. We're not looping; we're *transforming* the data in place, then counting what remains.

---

### Recall a memory pattern, extract the first match, hash its text

```scheme
;; Recall memories matching the pattern \"order:shipped\", take the first, hash its text.

(let ((memories (cortex/recall-pattern \"order:shipped\")))
  (if (or (eq? memories 'nan)
          (and (pair? memories) (eq? (car memories) 'escalate)))
      memories
      (if (null? memories)
          '(escalate \"no-matches\" \"no memories matched pattern\")
          (let ((first-mem (car memories)))
            (let ((text (cdr (assoc 'text first-mem))))
              (if (not text)
                  '(escalate \"malformed-memory\" \"first memory has no 'text field\")
                  (let ((hash (system/hash256 text)))
                    (if (eq? hash 'nan)
                        '(escalate \"hash-failed\" \"could not hash text\")
                        hash))))))))
```

Four checks, three verbs. The joints are explicit: recall, validate non-empty, extract a field, hash. Each `if` is a seam; each seam is honest.

---

## Four-stage pipelines: cross-namespace orchestration

When you chain verbs from different namespaces—`cortex/` → `model/` → `text/` → `mail/`—you're crossing the wired surface. Each verb speaks a different dialect; the pipeline translates between them. This is where mastery shows: you know which verb does what, you know their contracts, and you route failure at every boundary.

### Search CRM contacts, draft a reply with model/, normalize text, hash it

```scheme
;; Search CRM for contacts matching \"recent buyer\", take the first, draft a reply,
;; normalize the draft text, hash it, return the hash.

(let ((contacts (crm/contact-search \"recent buyer\")))
  (if (or (eq? contacts 'nan)
          (and (pair? contacts) (eq? (car contacts) 'escalate)))
      contacts
      (if (null? contacts)
          '(escalate \"no-contacts\" \"search returned no contacts\")
          (let ((first-contact (car contacts)))
            (let ((email (cdr (assoc 'email first-contact))))
              (if (not email)
                  '(escalate \"no-email\" \"first contact has no email field\")
                  (let ((draft (model/draft (string-append \"Write a follow-up email to \" email))))
                    (if (or (eq? draft 'nan)
                            (and (pair? draft) (eq? (car draft) 'escalate)))
                        draft
                        (let ((normalized (text/normalize draft)))
                          (if (eq? normalized 'nan)
                              '(escalate \"normalize-failed\" \"could not normalize draft\")
                              (let ((hash (system/hash256 normalized)))
                                (if (eq? hash 'nan)
                                    '(escalate \"hash-failed\" \"could not hash text\")
                                    hash))))))))))))
```

Four verbs, five checks: `crm/contact-search`, `model/draft`, `text/normalize`, `system/hash256`. Each comes from a different namespace; together they form a route from \"search contacts\" to \"hash of normalized draft.\" The pipeline is the program.

---

### Fetch Shopify orders, extract first order's line items, calculate total quantity, classify as \"large\" or \"small\"

```scheme
;; Fetch recent Shopify orders, take the first, sum line-item quantities,
;; classify the total as \"large\" (>10) or \"small\" (<=10).

(let ((orders (shopify/orders)))
  (if (or (eq? orders 'nan)
          (and (pair? orders) (eq? (car orders) 'escalate)))
      orders
      (if (null? orders)
          '(escalate \"no-orders\" \"orders list is empty\")
          (let ((first-order (car orders)))
            (let ((line-items (cdr (assoc 'line_items first-order))))
              (if (not line-items)
                  '(escalate \"no-line-items\" \"first order has no line_items field\")
                  (let ((total-qty (fold (lambda (item acc)
                                           (let ((qty (cdr (assoc 'quantity item))))
                                             (if qty (+ acc qty) acc)))
                                         0
                                         line-items)))
                    (if (> total-qty 10)
                        (cons 'classification \"large\")
                        (cons 'classification \"small\")))))))))
```

Four stages: fetch orders, extract line items, fold to sum quantities, classify. We introduce `fold` here—if you haven't seen it, it's a left-to-right accumulator: starts at 0, walks the list, adding each item's quantity. The final stage is a simple conditional; the route delivers a classification.

---

### Recall a memory, extract its timestamp, compute days since, decide if stale

```scheme
;; Recall a memory by key \"last-inventory-sync\", extract its timestamp,
;; compute days since, decide if >30 days = stale.

(let ((mem (cortex/recall \"last-inventory-sync\")))
  (if (or (eq? mem 'nan)
          (and (pair? mem) (eq? (car mem) 'escalate)))
      mem
      (let ((ts (cdr (assoc 'timestamp mem))))
        (if (not ts)
            '(escalate \"no-timestamp\" \"memory has no timestamp field\")
            (let ((days (time/days-since ts)))
              (if (eq? days 'nan)
                  '(escalate \"days-since-failed\" \"could not compute days since\")
                  (if (> days 30)
                      (cons 'status \"stale\")
                      (cons 'status \"fresh\"))))))))
```

Four stages: recall, extract timestamp, compute days, classify. Each verb does one thing; the pipeline does something none could do alone.

---

## Five-stage pipelines: the long route

A five-stage pipeline is a *route*. It crosses namespaces, transforms data at each joint, and escalates cleanly when a stage can't proceed. This is the top of the ramp for this chapter—these programs are genuinely hard, not because they use obscure features, but because they orchestrate many moving parts and handle failure honestly at every seam.

### Fetch Etsy listings, filter published, map to titles, take first 5, join into a summary string

```scheme
;; Fetch all Etsy listings, keep only published ones, extract titles,
;; take the first 5, join them with \" | \" into a single string.

(let ((listings (etsy/listings)))
  (if (or (eq? listings 'nan)
          (and (pair? listings) (eq? (car listings) 'escalate)))
      listings
      (let ((published (filter (lambda (listing)
                                 (let ((state (cdr (assoc 'state listing))))
                                   (equal? state \"active\")))
                               listings)))
        (if (null? published)
            '(escalate \"no-published\" \"no active listings found\")
            (let ((titles (map (lambda (listing)
                                 (cdr (assoc 'title listing)))
                               published)))
              (let ((first-five (if (> (length titles) 5)
                                    (list-head titles 5)
                                    titles)))
                (let ((summary (fold (lambda (title acc)
                                       (if (string=? acc \"\")
                                           title
                                           (string-append acc \" | \" title)))
                                     \"\"
                                     first-five)))
                  (if (string=? summary \"\")
                      '(escalate \"no-titles\" \"could not construct summary\")
                      summary))))))))
```

Five stages: fetch, filter, map, take-first-five, fold-into-string. We use `list-head` to slice the list (a standard Scheme form), then `fold` to join titles with \" | \". The route delivers a single string summarizing the first five published listings. If any stage fails—empty list, no titles—we escalate cleanly.

This is FORWARD at scale: each stage advances the computation. This is ESCAPE: we check at every joint. This is BACK: we don't build a complex data structure; we build the *simplest* structure that holds the answer.

---

### Fetch YouTube playlist items, extract video IDs, fetch video details, compute total duration, format as hours:minutes

```scheme
;; Fetch items from a YouTube playlist, extract video IDs, fetch details for each,
;; sum durations (in seconds), convert to hours:minutes format.

(let ((items (youtube/playlist-items-incremental \"PLxxxxxxxxxxx\")))
  (if (or (eq? items 'nan)
          (and (pair? items) (eq? (car items) 'escalate)))
      items
      (if (null? items)
          '(escalate \"no-items\" \"playlist is empty\")
          (let ((video-ids (map (lambda (item)
                                  (cdr (assoc 'videoId item)))
                                items)))
            (let ((videos (youtube/videos-list video-ids)))
              (if (or (eq? videos 'nan)
                      (and (pair? videos) (eq? (car videos) 'escalate)))
                  videos
                  (let ((durations (map (lambda (video)
                                          ;; duration is ISO8601 duration string, e.g. \"PT4M13S\"
                                          ;; We'll simulate parsing it as seconds (real code would parse).
                                          ;; For demo, assume each has a 'duration_seconds field.
                                          (let ((secs (cdr (assoc 'duration_seconds video))))
                                            (if secs secs 0)))
                                        videos)))
                    (let ((total-secs (fold + 0 durations)))
                      (let ((hours (quotient total-secs 3600))
                            (minutes (quotient (remainder total-secs 3600) 60)))
                        (string-append (number->string hours) \"h \"
                                       (number->string minutes) \"m\"))))))))))
```

Five stages: fetch playlist items, extract IDs, fetch video details, sum durations, format. We use `quotient` and `remainder` (core Scheme) to convert seconds to hours and minutes. The route delivers a human-readable duration string.

<!-- BUILD: needs ISO8601 duration parser if we want to handle real YouTube duration strings -->

